{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year = 2009 |Team = UCF Knights |Image = University of Central Florida UCF vertical text logo.svg |ImageSize = 100px |Conference = Conference USA |Division = East |ShortConference = C-USA |Record = 8â5 |ConfRecord = 6â2 |CoachRank = |APRank = |HeadCoach = [[George O'Leary]] |OffCoach = [[Charlie Taaffe]] |DefCoach = Dave Huxtable |OScheme = |DScheme = |StadiumArena = [[Bright House Networks Stadium]] |Champion = |BowlTourney = [[2009 St. Petersburg Bowl|St. Petersburg Bowl]] |BowlTourneyResult = L 45â24 vs. [[2009 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]] }} {{2009 Conference USA football standings}} The '''2009 UCF Knights football team''' represented the [[University of Central Florida]] in the [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. Their head coach was [[George O'Leary]], in his sixth season with the team. Coaching changes included new offensive coordinator [[Charlie Taaffe]]. For the third season, the [[UCF Knights football|UCF Knights]] played all of their home games at [[Bright House Networks Stadium]] on the school's main campus in [[Orlando, Florida]].<ref>[http://ucfathletics.cstv.com/facilities/ucf-brighthouse-bio.html Athletics Facilities - Bright House Networks Stadium]</ref>
All games were broadcast live on the UCF-[[ISP Sports]] radio network.<ref>[http://ucfathletics.cstv.com/multimedia/ucf-isp-radio-network.html UCF ISP Radio Network]</ref> The flagship was [[WYGM|WYGM "740 The Game"]] in Orlando, which had returned to a sports talk format after a year's absence but retained UCF's rights throughout. The games were called by Marc Daniels (play-by-play) and Gary Parris (color commentary), with Scott Adams and Jerry O'Neill as field reporters.
For the season, the Knights had an 8â5 record, 6â2 in [[Conference USA]], and placed second in the Eastern Division. The Knights finished the season with a six game conference winning streak, after starting conference play 0â2. The season included a 37â32 Homecoming win over the [[Houston Cougars football|Houston Cougars]], who were ranked #12 in the [[Coaches' Poll]], marking the first time in program history that the Knights had defeated a ranked opponent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=293182116|title=Central Florida holds off Keenum, No. 15 Houston|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=2010-02-19}}</ref> For the third time in five years, the Knights became bowl eligible and lost to [[2009 Rutgers Scarlet Knights football team|Rutgers]] in the [[2009 St. Petersburg Bowl|St. Petersburg Bowl]].
==Pre-Season== ===Coaching staff=== [[Image:George O'Leary-1.jpg||thumb|Head Coach George O'Leary]] On January 5, 2009, UCF hired [[Charlie Taaffe]] to be the teams new [[Offensive Coordinator]].<ref name="taaffe">http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/orl-sportsfbcucf04010409jan04,0,4978498.story Amid shakeup, UCF taps Taaffe to lead offense</ref> The change occurred amid a staff shake-up by Head Coach George O'Leary after a disappointing 2008 season. Tim Salem, whom Taaffe replaced, will transition to being the tight-ends coach and special-teams coordinator, 2008 quarterbacks coach George Godsey will move to be the running-backs coach, and Brent Key will move from being the tight-ends coach and special-teams coordinator to offensive-line coach.<ref name="taaffe"/>
